<TEXT>
a chinese dissident leader who fled his homeland 
after the crackdown on student protests in tiananmen square 
appeared on a television news show thursday and said he was no 
longer afraid of the chinese government 
i can no longer be afraid wuer kaixi said on the abc news 
program nightline late thursday ive already said what i 
have to do is to carry forward the cause of those who died 
i must do what they cannot have done i have no time to 
fear he said 
wuer and yan jiaqi prodemocracy fugitives from china arrived 
in chicago on wednesday for the first chinese students congress in 
the united states but failed to appear as scheduled at two news 
conferences 
wuer speaking from a television studio in chicago said 
conditions in china have grown more dangerous in recent weeks as 
the government continues its crackdown on students who led the 
prodemocracy demonstrations in beijing and other chinese cities 
he said it may not be possible for all student leaders to escape 
the country as he did 
im not sure anyone else will be able to come out he said 
but those who manage to come out should carry forward the tasks 
that they wish to carry out and those who died wished to carry 
out 
earlier thursday organizers of the student congress said wuer 
and yan were in danger 
they are in physical danger theyre really hiding minxin 
pei a harvard political science student and spokesman for the 
fledgling congress said at a news conference 
the visitors escaped from china after the military crushed 
student protests in beijings tiananmen square on june 4 they 
later surfaced in paris where they have been trying to rally 
worldwide support for the democracy movement in their homeland 
the pair were scheduled to participate in fridays formal 
opening of the threeday meeting of chinese students at american 
schools pei said the fbi is protecting the two leaders and he did 
not know their whereabouts 
wuer 21 was an organizer of the student demonstrations and 
yan 47 is the former director of the political science institute 
of the chinese academy of social sciences 
they are honored guests we want them to arrive safely and 
leave safely pei said 
pei said chinese officials have been harassing chinese student 
activists at us universities by making death threats during 
anonymous telephone calls he said officials from the chinese 
consulate in new york even visited his apartment called him a 
traitor and a fool for his prodemocracy activities and threatened 
big trouble if he persisted 
the congress of chinese students in the united states held at 
the chicago campus of the university of illinois is expected to 
draw 500 chinese students attending 154 us colleges and 
universities to discuss the democracy movement in china pei said 
our fellow brothers and sisters died in china and we should 
at least speak up for them said zhang xin a 33yearold student 
at the university of chicago who helped organize the congress it 
is our fundamental duty 
the congress will try to set up a radio station south of china 
said zhongdang pan a 31yearold journalism graduate student at 
the university of wisconsin 
transmission will be very powerful and we will put this 
transmission station very close to the border pan said 
pan said he also hopes to get a chinese language newspaper 
published in america and send copies to china 
the congress plans to mail and fax news to chinese offices 
hoping some of it will leak to the public the news will be 
addressed to businesses rather than to individuals to protect the 
people who receive the messages 
</TEXT>
