<TEXT>
a regional dispute that pits northwest timber 
interests against defenders of the spotted owl is spiraling into a 
national struggle over whether congress should impose extraordinary 
restrictions on the legal rights of environmentalists 
after winning a string of preliminary court victories blocking 
logging in vast sections of the ancient forests where the owls 
nest environmentalists say a temporary cease fire congress may 
impose would set a precedent that could be used to block judicial 
review of a wide range of federal decisions and actions 
environmentalists have enlisted the aid of organizations ranging 
from the american civil liberties union to the center for auto 
safety and the mexican american legal defense and education fund to 
the union of concerned scientists 
prohibiting citizen challenges to government actions places 
agencies above the law and violates fundamental principles of 
democratic government the groups said in a letter to senators 
while the groups noted that recent limitations on judicial 
review set by congress have involved public land and resource 
issues the practice could be used to bar citizen challenges to 
any government agency 
the interior appropriations bill is headed for a housesenate 
conference committee to iron out differences in the two versions 
before final passage by both houses the house version does not 
include the timber amendment 
an amendment attached by northwest lawmakers to the 
senatepassed bill would bar federal courts from enjoining or 
overturning any timber sale planned in the federal forests of 
oregon and washington known to contain spotted owls the ban would 
be in effect for 14 months 
in addition the amendment requires that environmentalists agree 
by oct 1 to release more than half of the roughly 2 billion board 
feet of timber enjoined for immediate sale if they dont the 
amendment would allow the forest service and the bureau of land 
management to proceed with the sales regardless of the injunctions 
jay hair president of the national wildlife federation said 
the amendment would allow the forest service to break virtually 
every environmental law congress has ever set 
northwest lawmakers said that even though they were reluctant to 
limit judicial review it was necessary if they were to keep the 
timber industry afloat until a permanent fix can be imposed 
lawmakers say mills in washington and oregon already are closing 
because of a severe shortage of timber resulting from the 
injunctions 
no one was eager to do this said rep al swift dwash 
but we needed some certainty in the timber supply and that 
couldnt be achieved if the sales were tied up in the courts this 
is only a shortterm fix 
sen brock adams dwash said that lawmakers were under 
great pressure to act and the amendment was aimed not only at 
ensuring mills had enough logs to operate but also at the beginning 
to protect some of the most significant stands of oldgrowth timber 
we did what we had to do said adams adding that despite 
the judicial limitations lawsuits challenging forest service and 
blm management plans for spotted owl habitat would be allow to 
continue on their merits 
lawmakers also said the precedent for limiting judicial review 
previously had been set by congress though adams said it had 
always been used sparingly 
congress in the 1930s limited the ability of federal courts to 
issue injunctions in labor strikes and in authorizing the alaska 
oil pipeline in the early 1970s congress said the issuance of 
construction and operation permits would not be subject to judicial 
review 
more recently congress enacted a statute in 1980 that allowed 
the secretary of transportation to impound federal highway funds 
despite court injunctions prohibiting it in 1983 congress 
exempted the mx missile program from federal environmental laws in 
the midst of an ongoing court challenge 
sen mark hatfield rore has four times over two years 
attached amendments to appropriations bill that barred appeals of 
several planned timber sales 
when the timber amendment was offered in the senate 
appropriations earlier this week three democratic senators spoke 
against it wyche fowler of georgia dale bumpers of arkansas and 
harry reid of nevada 
this is unprecedented said fowler adding that congress 
needed to be careful in approving such legislation despite the 
timber crisis 
