<TEXT>
the state army national guard has confirmed 
reports that a group of soldiers and civilians has been stealing 
military automatic weapons parts and using them to assemble and 
sell rifles machine guns and pistols 
lt col peter kutschera spokesman for the guard said thursday 
that over the past seven years a substantial number of parts were 
stolen in western new york state and used in the assembly of at 
least 58 automatic or semiautomatic guns 
but he said a report in thursdays gannett westchester 
newspapers that entire weapons were stolen from the guard was 
unfounded and that all weapons were accounted for 
kutschera said evidence gathered by guard investigators and the 
us bureau of alcohol tobacco and firearms was being presented to 
federal prosecutors in buffalo 
sen pete wilson rcalif a member of the senate armed 
services committee who has held hearings on military weapons 
thefts called for an investigation by the us general accounting 
office 
this could very well be a national problem wilson said 
unfortunately were not surprised that this exists since the 
defense departments inventory system is so riddled with problems 
kutschera said the ring appeared to succeed because the 
military which audits fully assembled weapons in its arsenals each 
month conducts no such audits of weapon parts including barrels 
stocks and firing mechanisms 
the guard kutschera said has no accounting procedures to 
detect the loss of parts if theyre pilfered on a small basis 
trigger units do have serial numbers however and the ring 
apparently did not steal any of them from the guard but instead 
purchased others from civilian sources 
kutschera said the guard learned of the ring in march 1988 
through an unrelated investigation of sales of stolen military 
equipment and clothing to an armynavy store in the buffalo area a 
soldier accused of involvement in those sales informed 
investigators about the weapons ring 
according to investigators records members of the ring stole 
weapons parts from guard repair and supply facilities mostly in 
buffalo and rochester and reassembled them with serialnumbered 
nonmilitary parts then they were traded or sold 
