india decided to resume withdrawing 
its peacekeeping troops friday on one of the island nations worst 
days of ethnic violence in which state tv reported 74 people were 
killed 
the decision to start pulling out more troops starting saturday 
averted a showdown with sri lankan president ranasinghe premadasa 
who had called the continued indian presence a threat to his 
nations independence 
the bush administration said it hopes the agreement saves lives 
we welcome this development and hope that india and sri lanka 
will be successful in reaching an agreement on a timetable for 
withdrawal that minimizes bloodshed while recognizing sri lankas 
sovereignty and independence said state department spokeswoman 
margaret tutwiler 
television in colombo said most of those who died were killed by 
sri lankan forces in areas where the indians are not deployed most 
died in the sinhalese heartland where extremists from premadasas 
own ethnic community have violently protested government peace 
efforts with the tamil minority and the continued presence of the 
indian troops 
tamils who make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese who account 
for 75 percent of the population and control the government and 
armed forces 
india spurred by its own politically powerful tamil minority of 
60 million sponsored the july 29 1987 peace accord designed to 
give tamils some autonomy in northern and eastern sri lanka but 
the biggest tamil guerrilla group the liberation tigers of tamil 
eelam reneged on the pact and started attacking the indians 
the telecast referred to those who died friday as 
troublemakers and disruptive elements terms frequently used 
for sinhalese radicals 
it said 16 people were killed when they attacked a police 
station at mannikhina near kandy about 60 miles northeast of 
colombo 
