curfew to stage antiindia demonstrations in the monargala district 
about 100 miles east of colombo state tv said 
five people were killed when they ignored a curfew in the 
predominantly tamil town of batticaloa 100 miles northeast of 
colombo the newscast said 
the other deaths were scattered throughout central and southern 
sri lanka 
premadasa originally sought the departure of all of indias 
45000 soldiers by saturday he announced the decision about an 
hour after it was publicized by government spokesmen in colombo and 
new delhi 
neither side indicated how many indian soldiers would leave but 
only a token force was likely to depart 
foreign minister ranjan wijeratne and six other sri lankan 
officials were to fly to new delhi to discuss a timetable for the 
withdrawal of the rest of the indian troops 
premadasa sought to portray the indian decision as a victory 
the twoyear indian military presence has fueled sri lankas ethnic 
violence among the tamil guerrillas that the indians were supposed 
to disarm and sinhalese extremists who denounced the indian 
presence as a violation of sri lankan sovereignty 
the protests staged against the continuance of the ipkf 
indian peace keeping force in our country can now cease he 
said by resorting to strikes and disruptive activities based on 
such protests we are causing damage and harm to ourselves it is 
our own people who get killed 
military troops and police were enforcing a nationwide curfew 
designed to thwart threatened disruptions by sinhalese radicals 
accused of killing 4000 people mostly sinhalese government 
officials and supporters since indian troops started arriving 
july 30 1987 
the curfew began thursday and was to continue until dawn sunday 
another 11000 people including 1000 indian soldiers have 
died in the tamil separatist war that started in 1983 
