<TEXT>
the communist leadership deeply 
split along regional lines is to blame for the slide into a 
nationalist precipice the official tanjug news agency said 
friday 
relations between yugoslavias ethnic groups have reached the 
lowest point in the postwar period tanjug said in an unsually 
blunt commentary as the communist partys central committee 
prepared for a meeting devoted to ethnic and nationalist tensions 
the meeting scheduled to open sunday and last for two days is 
being convened after a twomonth delay during which the quarrelsome 
leaders of yugoslavias republics tried to compromise on 
nationalistic differences 
the leadership in serbia the countrys largest and most 
populous republic on thursday attacked a draft declaration that 
will be taken up at the twoday committee meeting 
the declaration calls on the party to oppose all forms of 
nationalist discrimination including increasingly frequent 
demands for privileged treatment of larger nationalities at the 
expense of small ones 
in a statement serbias leadership branded the draft 
unacceptable because of its implication that serbs sought a 
privileged position within yugoslavia the leaderships of 
slovenia and croatia welcomed the draft as a good basis for 
discussion 
according to official statistics serbs make up about 40 percent 
of yugoslavias 23 million citizens while croats account for 20 
percent and slovenes for less than 10 percent macedonians 
montenegrins moslems ethnic albanians and several other 
minorities comprise the rest 
croatia and slovenia have traditionally been wary of what they 
claim are serbian attempts to dominate yugoslavia economically and 
politically serbs deny this contending that strong separatist and 
nationalist tendencies exist in both northern republics 
yugoslavias wealthiest regions 
what can the central committee and the communist party as a 
whole do to stop the slide into a nationalist precipice 
asked the tanjug commentary the geopolitically divided 
quarrelsome and confederalized party and its leaderships have 
themselves contributed decisively to the drastic worsening of 
ethnic tensions 
during the past month news media have reported a spate of 
nationalist incidents in various parts of the country 
particularly in resorts along the countrys adriatic coastline 
most of those resorts are in croatia 
the incidents usually involving brawls between local croats and 
serb tourists started after about 50000 serbs chanting 
nationalist slogans staged a mass rally in western croatia at the 
beginning of july 
in the past year the leaderships and media of the different 
regions have waged an allout propaganda feud over ways to overcome 
yugoslavias worst economic and social crisis 
the country a loose federation of six republics and two 
autonomous provinces is burdened with a 21 billion foreign debt 
a 700 percent annual inflation rate and stagnating economic growth 
the living standard has been in steep decline since 1980 and 
yugoslavia whose economic growth rate was second only to japans 
in the 1970s now has trouble manufacturing export products that 
measure up to western standards 
the communist leaderships of the republics divided between 
reformers and hardliners have been unable to agree on whether to 
introduce an open freemarket economy and greater political 
freedoms as a way out of the crisis 
