<TEXT>
the energy department on friday asked the 
nuclear regulatory commission to require an environmental impact 
statement and conduct a fullfledged hearing before deciding on the 
proposed dismantling of the shoreham nuclear power plant in new 
york 
energy secretary james watkins who has expressed strong 
opposition to the dismantling of the plant said in a letter to the 
commission that closing it for good would be a colossal mistake 
and increase the threat of power shortages in the northeast 
watkins also asked the commission to halt removal of the uranium 
fuel from the reactor now under way and to block plans to reduce 
the plants work force 
the long island lighting co has agreed with the state of new 
york to turn the 55 billion plant over to the long island power 
authority for 1 so that it can be dismantled in exchange for 
yielding the plant the company has received assurances of rate 
increases expected to be about 5 percent annually for the next 10 
years 
utility shareholders approved the plan june 28 and a new york 
state judge upheld the plan earlier this week 
state and local officials contend that a workable evacuation 
plan cannot be drawn up for the area around the new plant which 
though completed in 1985 and licensed in 1988 has yet to produce 
electricity commercially 
the 813megawatt plant is about 50 miles east of new york city 
on the northern shore of long island 
watkins said in his letter to kenneth carr chairman of the 
commission that dismantling shoreham would be contrary to every 
principle associated with the establishment and maintenance of a 
sensible national energy policy 
under federal law the commission must approve the transfer of 
the companys license to operate a nuclear power plant to the long 
island power authority the commission then must approve and 
oversee decommissioning 
watkins said the permanent shutdown of the plant would require 
greater use of fossil fuels resulting in environmental damage 
because of increased emissions that contribute to global warming 
and other environmental problems 
therefore the energy secretary argued the commission should 
conduct a full hearing and require a formal environmental impact 
statement before making a decision 
frank ingram a spokesman for the commission said carr and 
other commissioners have yet to review the letter he said the 
agency would have no immediate comment 
</TEXT>
