the discovery channel will become the latest 
cable tv programmer to scramble its satellitedelivered signal to 
fend off video pirates a company official said 
the landover mdbased company will begin scrambling its signal 
june 30 1990 said sandy mcgovern senior vice president of 
affiliate sales and relations 
socalled basic cable services such as cnn headline news espn 
and usa network already are scrambling their signals as are pay 
cable services such as home box office cinemax showtimethe movie 
channel and the disney channel 
backyard satellite dish owners and cable tv systems must have 
proper equipment to decode the scrambled signals 
mcgovern said thursday the company did not know how much 
business it was losing to theft but she said it counts 43 million 
paying subscribers while the ac nielsen ratings company reports 
a few million more homes than that are watching 
so we know theres some fairly significant theft she said 
scrambling began in january 1986 when hbo first encoded its 
signal more cable companies followed suit much to the dismay of 
backyard satellite dish owners many of whom paid about 2000 for 
their equipment 
congress passed the satellite home viewer copyright act last 
year guaranteeing access to the scrambled signals to backyard dish 
owners as long as they have paid for them 
the law was a boon to a new group of cable tv middlemen who put 
together packages of cable channels and sell them to satellite dish 
owners for monthly or yearly fees 
despite the scrambling however the cable industry claims it 
still loses millions of dollars to illegal decoding devices 
the discovery channel which began service in june 1985 offers 
nonfiction entertainment in the areas of nature science 
technology history and exploration 
it typically is provided to cable subscribers as part of basic 
packages of cable channels with the cable system operator paying 
the discovery channel a fee per subscriber 
