<TEXT>
sen howard metzenbaums recipe for better 
health has one major ingredient a heaping measure of accurate 
nutritional information 
for far too long we americans have been shopping in the 
dark the ohio democrat said thursday as he and other lawmakers 
joined together to support the proposed nutrition labeling and 
education act 
today were here to shine a little light on the food that 
lines our supermarket aisles 
the bill comes as food companies try to attract an increasingly 
healthconscious american public with products that are labeled 
lite or cholesterol free 
hearings on the proposed legislation will begin next week before 
the house subcommittee on health and the environment 
metzenbaum said the mandatory uniform labels required by the 
bill would eliminate what are at best confusing at worst 
downright deceptive labels voluntarily provided by many food 
manufacturers and processors 
about 55 percent of food includes some nutritional labeling 
this bill will in a sense give us a stomachimpact 
statement said rep jim cooper dtenn product labeling he 
said is a decade behind in giving consumers the kind of 
information they want 
the legislation has the support of 23 nutrition and health 
organizations including the american heart association center for 
science in the public interest american cancer society american 
dietetic association american college of physicians and public 
voice for food and health policy 
representatives from most of the groups appeared at a thursday 
news conference praising the bill for recognizing longstanding 
scientific research and educational efforts linking nutrition with 
deadly illnesses such as heart disease and cancer 
ellen haas of public voice for food and health policy a 
nutrition advocacy group said the legislation would refocus 
emphasis on food contents such as fat sodium and cholesterol and 
would give the consumer more understandable information 
the grocery manufacturers of america which represents 140 
national brand food manufacturers strongly supports efforts to 
comprehensively reform and standardize health and dietary 
information which appears on food labels said spokesman jeff 
nedelman 
but he said the bill had no provision to mandate national 
uniformity and would instead set specific requirements and put 
restrictions on the information that must be made available he 
also said it would not allow enough flexibility in labeling to 
account for future changes in scientific information 
karen brown a spokeswoman for the food marketing institute 
said her group had not examined the proposal but agreed that it was 
time to reexamine how nutritional information is provided 
the bill would 
make nutrition labeling mandatory on processed food sold in the 
united states 
require disclosure of certain essential pieces of information 
including the amount of fiber fat type of fat and amount of 
cholesterol 
use recommendations from the national academy of sciences to 
improve the format of labels and provide comparative context for 
the information 
provide clear and definite standards governing claims and 
statements involving such terms as lite and 
cholesterolfree 
metzenbaum criticized the food and drug administration for 
moving slowly on the issue 
sen john chafee rri echoed that concern in a written 
statement supporting the bill he said it had been 16 years since 
any fundamental change had been made in the way foods are labeled 
other cosponsors of the bill are democratic reps joe moakley of 
massachusetts and dan glickman of kansas 
