<TEXT>
westinghouse electric corp says a new 
configuration of electronic circuitry holds promise as an 
allinone radar system that will take up less space on stealth 
aircraft and offer advantages in other settings 
this is kind of a leapfrog this is the wave of the future 
said donald k alexander manager of antenna design and development 
at the westinghouse electronic systems group in baltimore 
on the heels of a 2 million defense grant westinghouse on 
thursday unveiled a project thats been in the works secretly for 
the last three years the company hopes to succeed in stacking 
wafers of microcircuits and connecting them into one system that 
would replace several bulkier and heavier radar systems 
the sixmonth grant is the first installment from the defense 
advanced research projects agency which is expected to contribute 
a total of 92 million over two years westinghouse had been 
developing the wafer radar with its own money and assistance from 
mcdonnelldouglas aircraft corp 
a single wafer radar system would be able to watch for aircraft 
or missiles follow them and map terrain and control weapons 
functions now performed by separate systems with separate antennas 
a combined radar system would have a special value in the 
stealth program because of the nature of the radardefeating planes 
the one thing you dont want to do with a stealthy airplane is 
cut holes in it for additional systems alexander said 
stealth technology relies in part on smooth uninterrupted 
surfaces of uniform material to slip undetected through the probing 
electronic beams of surveillance radar 
other applications for the new radar include lightweight space 
communications smart weapons control portable and mobile ground 
communications and submarine radar 
like todays most sophisticated radar the integrated wafer 
circuitry is made of gallium arsenide which conducts electricity 
much faster than silicon gallium arsenide circuits are also 
resistant to radiation 
the biggest drawback of gallium arsenide chips is that they are 
harder to make westinghouse said it has demonstrated manufacturing 
techniques that will help overcome the production problems 
the defense grant covers the design and fabrication of prototype 
wafer components the next steps would be to produce a useable size 
antenna and demonstrate it fullscale application might be six to 
10 years away alexander said 
