their number and timing could depend on the outcome of the 
closeddoor meeting where prosecutors will begin unfolding their 
case defense lawyers are expected to try to convince them not to 
seek charges against clients under the federal racketeer influenced 
and corrupt organizations act known as rico 
under rico convicted traders could lose their exchange seats 
and any assets judged to have been acquired through illegal actions 
federal prosecutors typically call in individual defense lawyers 
on the eve of major indictments for oneonone negotiations to seek 
cooperation in exchange for reduced charges 
but such a large meeting is unusual the tribune said noting 
that at least a dozen defense attorneys have been invited and the 
justice department has flown in its top rico expert 
the attorneys invited to meet with prosecutors represent clients 
who were told two weeks ago that they had 14 days to decide to 
cooperate with the government or face a racketeering charge the 
newspaper said 
the journal noted that the justice department could name the 
futures trading pits as racketeering enterprises an unlikely 
and unprecedented step 
