<TEXT>
the house voted friday to delay for one year a 
businessopposed tax rule that would encourage companies to expand 
the number of employees covered by health insurance 
the provision is included in a spending bill the house approved 
37626 and sent to the senate proponents hope that eventually 
enough pressure will build to convince congress to repeal the 
socalled section 89 entirely 
the house ways and means committee and the senate have already 
approved legislation that would revamp the regulations and delay 
them until jan 1 but would not rescind them 
section 89 enacted in 1986 requires employers to demonstrate 
that their health plans do not favor higherpaid workers 
some business groups have lobbied congress to drop the rule 
claiming that it is so complicated timeconsuming and expensive 
that it ends up having an effect that is the opposite of what was 
intended 
many of them employers may cancel their health insurance 
plans for employees rather than go through all the red tape of 
section 89 said rep louise slaughter dny 
employers in my district are hopping mad said rep silvio 
conte rmass 
the rule was to take effect last jan 1 but became so 
controversial that the treasury department delayed its 
implementation until oct 1 
the delay voted on friday was part of a bill providing 184 
billion for fiscal 1990 for the treasury the postal service and 
several smaller agencies fiscal 1990 begins oct 1 
the legislation provides 56 billion for the internal revenue 
service 363 million more than this year most of the increase is 
to strengthen the irss ability to enforce tax laws and to process 
returns 
the bill includes 148 million for the new office of national 
drug control policy headed by former education secretary william 
bennett most of which he is to disperse to law enforcement 
agencies 
the bill also contains 21 million to upgrade security at vice 
president dan quayles official residence at the naval observatory 
in washington and an additional 200000 to help remodel and 
renovate the third floor of the residence which is used by 
quayles three children 
