a midyear cattle inventory showed 1086 
million head on the nations farms and ranches as of july 1 
virtually unchanged from 1085 million a year ago the agriculture 
department said friday 
this stops the sevenyear trend of a declining cattle 
industry said the report by the departments national 
agricultural statistics service 
however the july 1 total was down 1 percent from the 1095 
million head reported two years ago last years inventory was said 
then to be the lowest since the july 1 count began in 1973 
in february the agency reported the jan 1 cattle inventory at 
a 28year low of fewer than 995 million head 
officials said the 1989 calf crop is expected to be 407 million 
head down fractionally from last year but up 2 percent from 1987 
the july 1 inventory of 1086 million head which includes 
calves and dairy cattle as well as beef stock included these 
categories 
beef cows 342 million up slightly from july 1 1988 and 1 
percent above july 1 1987 
milk cows 101 million down 1 percent from last year and 3 
percent below two years ago 
all heifers 500 pounds and over 167 million up 1 percent 
from last year but down 2 percent from two years ago 
beef replacement heifers 5 million up 4 percent from each of 
the past two years 
milk replacement heifers 45 million up 2 percent from last 
year but down 2 percent from two years ago 
other heifers 72 million down 1 percent from a year ago and 
down 5 percent from two years ago 
steers weighing 500 pounds and over 145 million unchanged 
from last year but down 2 percent from two years ago 
bulls weighing 500 pounds and over 22 million unchanged from 
both years 
calves under 500 pounds 309 million down fractionally from 
last year and down 1 percent from two years ago 
</TEXT>
