<TEXT>
federal regulators closed three more texas banks 
thursday bringing to 99 the total number failures in the state 
this year only 14 less than all of last year 
in two of thursdays closures all deposits were transferred to 
new owners but at forestwood national bank of dallas only deposits 
up to the 100000 insured limit were transferred 
the federal office of the comptroller of the currency closed 
forestwoods two branches citing problems brought on by a 
continuing real estate collapse combined with liberal and 
aggressive lending practices 
occ senior deputy comptroller frank maguire also closed brushy 
creek national bank in round rock with the fdic transferring the 
banks deposits and some other liabilities to union national bank 
in austin for a 1000 premium 
and texas banking commissioner kenneth w littlefield shut the 
texas bank amp trust co in sweetwater about 42 miles west of 
abilene 
the occ said 10yearold forestwood had assets of about 614 
million the federal deposit insurance corp named as receiver of 
the bank approved the transfer of insured deposits and secured 
liabilities to comerica banktexas in dallas 
in most failures the fdic has transferred all deposits even 
those above the insurance limit but it said only insured deposits 
were transferred because of an inability to determine the value 
of the banks assets and undeterminable exposure in significant 
contingent liabilities 
comerica bank is paying the fdic 200000 for the right to 
receive the deposits and it will purchase 394 million of the 
failed banks assets the fdic will retain assets with a book value 
of about 22 million 
union will assume 101 million in 2400 brushy creek deposit 
accounts and has agreed to purchase certain brushy creek assets for 
65 million with options to purchase more the fdic also will 
provide 35 million in assistance and retain assets with a book 
value of 35 million 
the occ said brushy creek had assets of 101 million 
the fdic sold the texas bank amp trust cos 356 million in 
deposits to first national bank in sweetwater for 457000 first 
national also agreed to purchase 291 million of the failed banks 
assets 
the fdic will advance first national 61 million in assistance 
plus retain assets with a book value of 75 million 
